{
    "unitNumber": 20,
    "text": {
        "title": "Reflexive Pronouns",
        "sections": [
            {
                "title": "Reflexive Pronouns",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 20.01,
                        "content": "Reflexive pronouns correspond to ‘myself’, ‘yourself’, etc. in phrases like ‘you flatter yourself’, ‘the cat’s licking itself’, ‘the recorder’s switched itself off’. In such cases, the subject and the object of the verb are the same person or thing:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Ti** guardi sempre allo specchio.", "You always look at yourself in the mirror."],
                                ["**Mi** lavo.", "I get washed. [lit. I wash myself]"],
                                ["Anna **si** veste per la festa.", "Anna’s getting dressed for the party. [lit. Anna’s dressing herself]"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "These examples show how the reflexive pronouns are the direct objects of the verbs **lavare**, **guardare**, and **vestire** and denote the same person as the **subject**."
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "There are very many verbs which can be used in the **reflexive form** in Italian and which do not correspond to English reflexive verbs. Here is a list of some of the most common ones:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["addormentarsi", "to fall asleep [lit. to send oneself to sleep]"],
                                ["alzarsi", "to get up [lit. to raise oneself]"],
                                ["annoiarsi", "to get/be bored [lit. to bore oneself]"],
                                ["dimenticarsi", "to forget [lit. to forget oneself]"],
                                ["lavarsi", "to get washed [lit. to wash oneself]"],
                                ["offendersi", "to take offence [lit. to offend oneself]"],
                                ["ricordarsi", "to remember [lit. to recall oneself]"],
                                ["riposarsi", "to rest [lit. to rest oneself]"],
                                ["sbagliarsi", "to be wrong/mistaken [lit. to mistake oneself]"],
                                ["scusarsi", "to apologise [lit. to excuse oneself]"],
                                ["sedersi", "to sit down [lit. to seat oneself]"],
                                ["sentirsi", "to feel (well, ill, etc.) [lit. to feel oneself]"],
                                ["svegliarsi", "to wake up [lit. to waken oneself]"],
                                ["vestirsi", "to get dressed [lit. to dress oneself]"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 2,
                        "content": "The forms of the reflexive pronouns are as follows:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Person", "Reflexive Pronoun"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["mi", "myself"],
                                ["ti", "yourself"],
                                ["si", "himself/herself/itself"],
                                ["ci", "ourselves"],
                                ["vi", "yourselves"],
                                ["si", "themselves"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["A che ora ti alzi, la mattina?", "What time do you get up in the morning?"],
                                ["Paolo si* sveglia sempre tardi.", "Paolo always wakes up late."],
                                ["Maria si* annoia.", "Maria is bored."],
                                ["I tuoi amici si* sbagliano: il concerto non è stasera.", "Your friends are wrong: the concert is not tonight."],
                                ["Le mie amiche si* divertono.", "My friends are enjoying themselves"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "* Note that the third person singular and plural pronoun **si** is the same."
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "As can be seen from the examples, reflexive pronouns are always placed before the verb."
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 3,
                        "content": "The negative is formed, as usual, by placing non before the pronoun:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["Lorenzo non si annoia mai.", "Lorenzo never gets/is never bored."],
                                ["Non ti diverti?", "Aren’t you enjoying yourself?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 4,
                        "content": "For the formal form, the pronoun si (third person singular and plural) is used. In the plural, however, the pronoun vi is most frequently used:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["Come si sente, Signora?", "How are you feeling, Madam?"],
                                ["Vi divertite, Signori Rasi?", "Are you enjoying yourselves Mr and Mrs Rasi?"],
                                ["Si divertono, Signori Rasi?", "Are you enjoying yourselves Mr and Mrs Rasi?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 5,
                        "content": "The plural forms of the reflexive pronouns (ci, vi, si) are also used as reciprocal pronouns, corresponding to the English ‘each other’:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["Paolo e io non ci sopportiamo.", "Paolo and I can’t stand each other."],
                                ["Perché vi guardate?", "Why are you looking at each other?"],
                                ["Alfredo e Pia non si parlano più.", "Alfredo and Pia don’t talk to each other any more."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 6,
                        "content": "Reflexive pronouns can also be used, in contemporary spoken Italian, as indirect objects. One such use is to stress that the action expressed by the verb is to the advantage of the subject (cf. English ‘I’m making myself a coffee’ [i.e. a coffee for myself], ‘They’re going to have themselves some fun’ [i.e. some fun for themselves]):",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["Mi mangio un panino.", "I’m going to eat a sandwich."],
                                ["Perché non ci facciamo una partita a carte?", "Why don’t we have a game of cards?"],
                                ["Paolo si mangia sempre tutti i biscotti.", "Paolo always eats all the biscuits."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 7,
                        "content": " Another common use of the Italian reflexive pronoun occurs in cases like the following, where English would use a possessive adjective (‘my’, ‘your’, etc.) rather than a reflexive pronoun:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows":[
                                ["Mi lavo le mani.", "I wash my hands."],
                                ["Ti metti il cappotto?", "Are you going to put your coat on?"],
                                ["Anna si lava i capelli tutti i giorni.", "Anna washes her hair every day."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 8,
                        "content": "In compound tenses like the present perfect, reflexive verbs always take the auxiliary **essere**, and the past participle agrees in gender and number with the subject:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Paolo si ***è*** svegliat***o*** tardi.", "Paolo woke up late."],
                                ["Maria si ***è*** annoiat***a***", "Maria got bored."],
                                ["Vittorio, a che ora ***ti*** sei alzat***o***?", "Vittorio, what time did you get up?"],
                                ["Paolo e Francesca si ***sono*** sposat***i***.", "Paolo and Francesca have got married."],
                                ["Claudio e Anna si ***sono*** lavat***i*** le mani.", "Claudio and Anna washed their hands."],
                                ["Sabina si ***è*** mangiat***a*** un panino.", "Sabina ate a sandwich."],
                                ["Si ***sono*** fatt***i*** un caffè", "They made (themselves) a coffee."]

                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 9,
                        "content": "The reflexive pronouns, like all unstressed pronouns, can be attached to the infinitive of a verb (mainly after **dovere**, **potere**, **volere**, or **sapere**). In these sentences, when the main verb is in the present perfect (or any other compound tense), the auxiliary is **avere**, and the past participle does not agree:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Devo **alzarmi** presto.", "I’ve got to get up early."],
                                ["Mio fratello non vuole **lavarsi**.", "My brother doesn’t want to wash."],
                                ["Paolo e Francesca hanno voluto **sposarsi**.", "Paolo and Francesca wanted to get married."],
                                ["Non abbiamo potuto **lavarci**.", "We couldn’t wash."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "However, when the reflexive pronoun is not attached to the infinitive, the auxiliary verb must be **essere**, and the past participle does agree:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Paolo e Francesca **si sono voluti** sposare.", "Paolo and Francesca wanted to get married."],
                                ["Non ci siamo potuti lavare.", "We couldn’t wash."],
                                ["Vi siete dovuti fermare per la notte?", "Did you have to stop for the night?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Stressed Forms",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 10,
                        "content": "The reflexive pronouns also have stressed forms which are used, like the stressed forms of other pronouns, for emphasis and after a preposition. These forms are often reinforced by the adjective **stesso**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Person", "Stressed Reflexive Pronoun", "With stesso"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["me or me stesso/stessa", "myself"],
                                ["te or te stesso/stessa", "yourself"],
                                ["sé or se* stesso/stessa", "himself/herself/itself"],
                                ["noi or noi stessi/stesse", "ourselves"],
                                ["voi or voi stessi/stesse", "yourselves"],
                                ["sé or se* stessi/stesse", "themselves"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Franca ama solo sé/se* stessa.", "Franca only loves herself"],
                                ["Pensi solo a te/te stesso!", "You only think of yourself!"],
                                ["Quei due sono davvero noiosi: parlano solo di sè/se* stessi.", "Those two are really boring: they only talk about themselves."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "* Note that **sé** does not have an accent when it is used with **stesso**."
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
